A = \begin{bmatrix} 
1 & 2 & 3 \\ 
0 & -1 & 2 \\
1 & 1 & 3 
\end{bmatrix}

First, we can subtract the first row from the third row:

A = \begin{bmatrix} 
1 & 2 & 3 \\ 
0 & -1 & 2 \\
0 & -1 & 0 
\end{bmatrix}

Next, we can add the second row to the third row:

A = \begin{bmatrix} 
1 & 2 & 3 \\ 
0 & -1 & 2 \\
0 & 0 & 2 
\end{bmatrix}

Now the matrix is in row echelon form. We can see that there are no rows of zeros, so the rank of the matrix A is equal to the number of rows, which is 3. Therefore, the rank of the matrix A is 3.
